<p>
  I like comforting/validating my friends when comfort/validation <i><b>is not the bulk of what I provide to said friend.</b></i> And I like comforting/validating my friends when DMing me about an emotion-affecting problem is an act of communication instead of an act of emotional-regulation or experience processing.
</p>
<p>
  If, while typing, the act of DMing me a vent feels like emotional-regulation or linguistically processing something that has happened (especially fresh off the event that you're needing to vent from), please stop and take some deep breaths. <br>
  My presence as an audience is not needed. A living, breathing, body to externally validate is not needed. Having me be an external tool for event-processing/emotional regulation causes me to feel stressed and fatigued. Basically whatever you feel: I feel.
</p>
<p>
  You can achieve the same emotional-regulation and linguistic processing of an event by journaling about it. No pen and paper required, if you don't want. You can use {% extLink "Obsidian", "https://obsidian.md" %} or a private messaging server with just you in it.
</p>
<p>
  The funny thing is, after you actually, honestly, process something for yourself, <i><b>by</b> yourself</i> for the first time, it actually makes it easier for you to vent to others in a way that engages them conversationally instead of just talking at them and waiting for validation signals. (That is, <i>if</i> you even need to vent to others <i><b>at all!</b></i> Sometimes after processing and self-validating in a journal, you find you don't need to vent to others about That Specific Thing anymore.)
</p>

